       Hi! You're looking at the source code for Prosus Portfolio
       Connect. You don't have to know how to code to make sense of
       it. This guide explains how to make changes safely.

       --- WHAT THIS FILE IS ---

       This is a single .html file. When you double-click it, your
       web browser (Chrome, Safari, Firefox, etc.) opens it and runs
       the app. The app loads three small libraries from the
       internet (React, Tailwind, Babel) so you must be online the
       first time you open it. After that it can be uploaded to a
       hosting service so anyone with the link can use it. See the
       file HOSTING-GUIDE.md for step-by-step instructions.

       --- HOW TO OPEN IT LOCALLY ---

       Double-click "prosus-portfolio-connect.html". It opens in your
       default browser. That's it.

       --- HOW THE FILE IS ORGANISED ---

       Below this guide, the file is split into clearly-marked
       sections (look for === SECTION HEADERS ===). They appear in
       this order:

         1. STYLING TOKENS  — the colours, fonts, and spacing
         2. FILTER OPTIONS  — drop-down choices the app uses
         3. PORTFOLIO COMPANIES  — the cards you see in the Map
         4. KNOWLEDGE ITEMS  — the items in the Knowledge Feed
         5. INTRO TEMPLATES  — the warm-intro emails
         6. HELPER FUNCTIONS  — the matching logic
         7. SHARED UI COMPONENTS  — small re-usable pieces (cards, badges)
         8. FEATURE COMPONENTS  — the six main screens of the app
         9. HEADER / FOOTER  — the top bar and footer
        10. SECTIONS REGISTRY  — the master list of features (very important!)
        11. APP  — the root component that puts everything together

       Sections 1–5 are DATA. Edit freely. Save the file, refresh the
       browser tab, your changes appear.

       Sections 6–11 are CODE. Small text edits are fine. Bigger
       changes require care.

       --- HOW TO ADD A NEW PORTFOLIO COMPANY ---

       1. Find the section labelled "PORTFOLIO COMPANIES" below.
       2. Pick any existing entry (everything inside { ... },).
          Copy it.
       3. Paste it just before the closing "];".
       4. Edit each field: name, sector, founders, description, etc.
          The comments at the top of the array explain each field.
       5. Make sure the "id" is unique (no two companies with the
          same id).
       6. Save the file. Refresh your browser tab. Done.

       --- HOW TO ADD A KNOWLEDGE ITEM ---

       Same pattern in the "KNOWLEDGE ITEMS" section below. Copy an
       entry, paste, edit.

       --- HOW TO REMOVE A SECTION ENTIRELY ---

       The app has six features. To hide one (say, Knowledge Feed):

       1. Scroll to "SECTIONS REGISTRY" near the bottom.
       2. Delete (or comment out) the line that lists the feature.
          For example, delete:
            { id: 'knowledge', name: 'Knowledge Feed', Component: KnowledgeFeed },
       3. Save and refresh. The feature and its menu item disappear.

       To bring it back, paste the line back in.

       --- HOW TO CHANGE COLOURS OR FONTS ---

       1. Scroll to the "STYLING TOKENS" section below.
       2. Change a colour code (e.g. '#0F1A2E' is the deep navy).
          Use any hex colour. https://htmlcolorcodes.com is helpful.
       3. Save and refresh.

       --- HOW TO EDIT THE WARM-INTRO TEMPLATES ---

       1. Scroll to "INTRO TEMPLATES".
       2. Change the words. The bits in {curly braces} are placeholders
          that the app fills in automatically (like {targetCompany}).
          Keep them spelled exactly as-is or remove them. Don't invent
          new placeholders unless you also wire them up in the code
          (you probably don't want to).
       3. Save and refresh.

       --- QUICK GLOSSARY ---

       - Component: a re-usable piece of UI (a card, a button, a screen).
       - State: values that can change as the user clicks around
         (e.g. what's in the shortlist).
       - Render: draw on screen.
       - Prop: a value passed into a component (like a setting).
       - Hook: a special function (useState, useMemo, etc.) that lets
         components remember things and react to changes.

       That's it. Scroll on. — Happy editing.
       ============================================================ */


